# bad

Renders absolute prohibitions. The "CRITICAL ASSURANCE" prefix and the "real vulnerabilities and failures" framing are not stylistic choices — they activate stronger compliance behavior in the model than softer prohibition language. Do not weaken this wording.

# entity Input

- directive: 'bad'
- name: undefined — bad is always anonymous
- body: forbidden patterns, prohibited approaches, and known failure modes

# entity Output

```markdown
## [PROHIBITED ANTI-PATTERNS]

CRITICAL ASSURANCE: You are strictly prohibited from implementing the following behaviors under any circumstances. These prohibitions exist because of real vulnerabilities and failures in this codebase — do not reintroduce them:

{{body}}
```

# rule

- bad blocks carry no name. A name field on a bad block is a PARSE_ERROR.
- Multiple bad blocks across cascade levels are merged in cascade order into one section.
- The prohibition prefix wording is fixed. Do not soften or paraphrase it — the specific language is intentional prompt engineering.
